ce:section.ce:para:
TEM image of purified N-doped C-dots on carbon coated copper grid is shown on Fig. 1
                        A. C-dots appear on the micrograph as uniform in size and spherical shape nanoparticles with an average diameter less than 2 nm. This result was obtain after significantly subtraction of the granularity background of the carbon film. And even then it was challenge to distinguish the right location and the outlines of the low contrasted nanoparticles on the TEM image, because the imaging of predominantly carbon structures on carbon grids does not allow the precise determination of the objects. The difficulty to obtain clear TEM data of the ultrasmall individual C-dots due to their small size was overcome by combining of DLS and AFM methods. To confirm the size distribution of N-doped C-dots we measured nanoparticles hydrodynamic diameter by DLS as shown on Fig. 1B. DLS analysis demonstrate that the nanoparticles were distributed in the range of 1–1.5 nm with an average value of ˜ 1.2 nm. This average value was supported unambiguously by AFM measurement of the height profile of C-dots dispersed onto highly oriented pyrolytic graphite substrate as shown on Fig. 1C. The formed aggregate (white spot) consisted of immobilized homogeneous monolayer of N-doped C-dots on mica film. The monolayer was easily observed (topographic image upside) and thus, its reliable height profiles 1.2–1.3 nm (graphic analysis downside) were obtained. Based on the provided microscopic and spectroscopic data (as shown on Fig. 2
                        ) we assumed that the N-doped C-dots consisted mainly graphite-based nanosheets (polyaromatic carbon domains) immersed in an amorphous sp3-hybridized carbon matrix as proposed in the illustrated chemical model on the upper AFM image (Fig. 1C) [26]. Other groups also reported the existence of polyaromatic domains of condensed 6 or 10 aromatic rings, surrounded with amorphous sp3-carbon framework [27]. The sp2-hybridized domains form a carbogenic core conducting network which allows freely shuttling of the electrons [28] and can even act as an electron reservoir to trap the emitted electrons and transfer to O2 molecules adsorbed on C-dots surface [29]. The transferring of electrons in an ORR process is an important parameter in respect of the electrocatalyst efficiency [30].
